===subject:reply to Heather
===from:Yvonne Turner
===date:Sun Jun 29 12:00:34 2003
===message:In our recent war the public was led to believe that Saddam had a major supply of weapons of mass destruction. Although nothing has been found to date, there still may be the possibility that the weapons existed.  I am not arguing that point.  But since there weren't any weapons found, and there wasn't a declaration of war on the United States from Saddam (none that I am aware of), I want to understand what was the rush to go to war.  How is America better today, than it was before we went to war?
<p>
Although the decision is made collectively from Congress, a president has much power to influence his peers.  Also the way our government is setup, the president can declare war.  
<p>
Although I may not have stood in the shoes of soldier's that have served in the Middle East or other wars, I have had close friends and family who have.  Any time there is a threat of war, the main topic of our discussions is why.  Of course, they realized once they joined the military, they joined to support their country, but I don't think they realized they joined to support the political motives of our leaders.  Some of the wars the U.S. were involved in were not our battles to fight.
<p>
Although many may not agree with my opinions, I feel very strongly about staying out of other people's business affairs unless their is a direct impact or threat to our country.  If our leaders really want to fight a war, they should use our soldiers to fight a war against drugs, crime, and other torturous acts here in the United States.  I feel we spend too much time protecting people in other countries, and we forget about our own.  We have spent a countless number of dollars fighting a war in the Middle East, but in some neighborhoods in the United States, students can't get a proper education because crimes and drugs have taken over.    
=========yorg=========
===subject:For Stephanie
===from:Laura Johnson
===date:Sun Jun 29 20:10:48 2003
===message:Regarding your comments on the attack on the World Trade Center: There are people out there who passionately hate America, because they believe we are the cause of, or at least largely contribute to, the poverty and misery in which they live. We had every right to retaliate against Osama bin Laden and the Taliban. However, this pre-emptive attack on Iraq had absolutely positively nothing to do with the World Trade Center. Saddam Hussein had nothing to do with the World Trade Center. I think that is a distinction that desperately needs to made, as so many Americans seem to be horribly mistaken about who was behind that WTC attack and about why we are in Iraq.
=========yorg=========
